=== Equipment ===
[[File:Challenger II.jpg|200px|right|thumb|[[Challenger 2|Challenger II]] [[main battle tank]].]]
[[File:Warrior Infantry Fighting Vehicle.jpg|right|200px|thumb|[[Warrior IFV]].]]
[[File:Westland apache wah-64d longbow zj206 arp.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[AgustaWestland Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]]]
[[File:SA-80 rifle 1996.jpg|thumb|200px|[[SA80|L85A1 Rifle (now replaced by the L85A2)]].]]
{{main|Modern equipment of the British Army}}

'''Infantry'''
The basic infantry weapon of the British Army is the [[SA80|L85A2]] assault rifle, sometimes equipped with an [[L17A2 UGL|L17A2]] underbarrel grenade launcher and with several variants such as the [[L86 LSW|L86A2]], the Light Support Weapon (LSW) and the L22A2 carbine variant, issued to tank crews. Support fire is provided by the [[FN Minimi]] light machine gun and the [[L7 (machine gun)|L7 General Purpose Machine Gun]] (GPMG); indirect fire by [[British 51&nbsp;mm Mortar|51]] and [[L16 81mm Mortar|81&nbsp;mm mortars]]. Sniper rifles used include the [[L118A1]]&nbsp;7.62&nbsp;mm, the [[L115A3]] and the [[AW50F]], all produced by [[Accuracy International]]. Some units use the [[M82 Barrett rifle|L82A1]]&nbsp;.50 calibre Barrett sniper rifle. More recently the [[L128A1]] (Benelli M4) 'combat shotgun' has been adopted, and is intended for close quarters combat in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/equipment/support-weapons/17927.aspx |title=Combat Shotgun – British Army Website |publisher=Army.mod.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-10-22|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5uKgzKZWI |archivedate = 18 November 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2009/04/10/british-armys-new-combat-shotgun/ |title=British Army’s new combat shotgun |publisher=The Firearm Blog |date=10 April 2009 |accessdate=2010-10-22|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5uKgzjJBU |archivedate = 18 November 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref>

'''Armour'''
The British Army's [[main battle tank]] is [[Challenger 2]].<ref>[http://www.baesystems.com/ProductsServices/l_and_a_ls_challenger.html Challenger 2] BA Systems</ref><ref>[http://www.dasa.mod.uk/publications/equipment/CFE-vehicles-and-aircraft/2013/2013.pdf "UKDS 2013"]</ref> Other armoured vehicles include [[MWMIK|Supacat "Jackal" MWMIK]] and the [[Iveco LMV|Iveco "Panther" CLV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense-update.com/products/m/MLV.htm |title=Multi-role Light Vehicle |publisher=Defense-update.com |date=26 July 2006 |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> The [[Warrior Infantry Fighting Vehicle]] is the primary [[armoured personnel carrier]], although many variants of the [[Combat Vehicle Reconnaissance (tracked)]] are used, as well as the [[Saxon APC]] and [[FV430 series]] now being re-engined and uparmoured and returned to front line service as [[Bulldog APC|Bulldog]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sloppyjalopy.com/fv432.htm |title=FV 432 |publisher=Sloppyjalopy.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> The British Army commonly uses the [[Land Rover Wolf]] and [[Land Rover Defender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.landrover.com/gb/en/lr/defender/ |title=Land Rover Defender |publisher=Landrover.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>

'''Artillery'''
The Army uses three main artillery systems: the [[MLRS|Multi Launch Rocket System]] (MLRS), [[AS-90]] and [[L118]]. The MLRS was first used operationally in [[Operation Granby]] and has a range of {{convert|70|km|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/equipment/artillery-air-defence/1512.aspx GMLRS] British Army</ref> The AS-90 is a 155&nbsp;mm self-propelled gun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armedforces.co.uk/army/listings/l0046.html |title=AS-90 |publisher=Armedforces.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> The L118 Light Gun is a 105&nbsp;mm towed gun used primarily in support of 16 Air Assault Brigade, 19 Light Brigade and 3 Commando Brigade ([[Royal Marines]]).<ref>[http://www.baesystems.com/ProductsServices/l_and_a_ls_105mm_light_gun.html 105 mm Light Gun] BAe Systems</ref> The [[Rapier (missile)|Rapier FSC Missile System]] is the Army's primary battlefield air defence system, widely deployed since the [[Falklands War]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armedforces-int.com/projects/rapier_missile.html |title=Rapier missile |publisher=Armedforces-int.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> and the [[Starstreak (missile)|Starstreak HVM]] (High Velocity Missile) is a surface-to-air weapon, launched either by a single soldier or from a vehicle-mounted launcher.<ref>[http://www.janes.com/events/exhibitions/dsei2007/sections/daily/day1/starstreak-ii-sighted.shtml Starstreak II sighted] Janes</ref>

'''Army Aviation'''
The [[British Army Air Corps|Army Air Corps]] (AAC) provide direct aviation support for the Army, although the RAF also contribute by providing support helicopters. The primary attack helicopter is the [[Westland WAH-64 Apache]], a license-built, modified version of the US [[AH-64 Apache]] that replaced the Westland Lynx AH7 in the anti-tank role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/equipment/aircraft/1531.aspx |title=Apache |publisher=Army.mod.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> The [[Westland Lynx|Lynx]] remains in service as an armed escort, surveillance and light utility helicopter. Other types are used in specialised roles e.g. the [[Westland Gazelle]] as a light surveillance aircraft<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/equipment/aircraft/1533.aspx Gazelle] British Army</ref> and the [[Bell 212]] for support in specific Jungle / 'hot and high' environments <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vectorsite.net/avhuey.html |title=Bell Huey |publisher=Vectorsite.net |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>  The [[Eurocopter Dauphin|Eurocopter AS 365N Dauphin]] is used for Special Operations Aviation<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Janes Defence Weekly, Vol. 45, Issue 50 |date=10 December 2008|page=10|title=UK Army Air Corps received Dauphins|author=Tim Ripley}}</ref> and the [[Britten-Norman Islander]] is a light fixed-wing aircraft used for airborne reconnaissance and command and control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britten-norman.com/products/bn2b/ |title=Islander |publisher=Britten-norman.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>

== Recent and current conflicts ==

=== Persian Gulf War ===
{{Main|Gulf War|Operation Granby}}
The ending of the [[Cold War]] saw a significant cut in manpower, as outlined in the [[Options for Change]] review.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1990/jul/25/defence-options-for-change Defence (Options for Change)] Hansard, 25 July 1990</ref> Despite this, the Army has been deployed in an increasingly global role, and contributed 50,000 troops to the coalition force that fought [[Iraq]] in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2004/jun/11/iraq.military|title=50,000 troops in Gulf illness scare|work=The Guardian|date=11 June 2004}}</ref> British forces were put in control of [[Kuwait]] after it was liberated.
47 British Military personnel died during the Persian Gulf War.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/SUPREME+SACRIFICE%3B+British+soldier+killed+in+Iraq+was+unemployed+TA...-a0107281788 |title=Supreme sacrifice: British soldier killed in Iraq was unemployed TA man |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date=28 August 2003 |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref>

=== Balkans conflicts ===
{{Main|Yugoslav wars}}
The British Army was deployed to [[Yugoslavia]] in 1992; initially this force formed part of the [[United Nations Protection Force]].<ref>Mallinson, p. 446</ref> In 1995 command was transferred to [[IFOR]] and then to [[SFOR]].<ref>Mallinson, p. 447</ref> Currently troops are under the command of [[EUFOR]]. Over 10,000 troops were sent. In 1999 British forces under the command of SFOR were sent to [[Kosovo]] during the conflict there. Command was subsequently transferred to [[Kosovo Force|KFOR]].<ref>Mallinson, p. 448</ref> Between early 1993 and June 2010, 72 British military personnel died on operations in the former Yugoslavian countries of Bosnia, Kosovo and Macedonia.<ref>[http://www.mod.uk/defenceinternet/factsheets/operationsfactsheets/balkansbritishfatalities.htm Operations in the Balkans: British Fatalities] Defence factsheet</ref>

=== War in Afghanistan ===
{{Main|War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|Operation Herrick}}
[[File:BritishPatrolHelmand01.jpg|thumb|right|British soldiers in May 2007, during the [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|War in Afghanistan]].]]
[[File:3 Para Helmand 2007.jpg|thumb|3 Para in combat in Helmand Province, Afghanistan]]
In November 2001 the United Kingdom, as a part of [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] with the United States, invaded [[Afghanistan]] to topple the [[Taliban]].<ref>Mallinson, p. 452</ref> The [[British 3rd Infantry Division|3rd Division]] were deployed in [[Kabul]], to assist in the liberation of the troubled capital. The Royal Marines' [[3 Commando Brigade]] (part of the [[Royal Navy]] but including a number of Army units), also swept the mountains.<ref>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/FactSheets/OperationsInAfghanistanChronologyOfEventsSeptember2001December2002.htm Operations in Afghanistan: Chronology of Events, September 2001 – December 2002] Defence factsheet</ref> The British Army is today concentrating on fighting [[Taliban]] forces and bringing security to Helmand province. Approximately 7,900 British troops (including marines, airmen and sailors) are currently in Afghanistan, making it the second largest force after the US. Around 500 extra British troops were deployed in 2009, bringing the British Army deployment total up to 9,500 (excluding Special Forces).<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8305922.stm UK sends 500 more to Afghanistan] BBC News, 15 October 2009</ref> In December 2012 Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] announced that 3,800 troops - almost half of the force serving in Helmand Province - would be withdrawn during 2013 with numbers to fall to approximately 5,200.<ref name=ukwithdrawal>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-20778561 UK to withdraw 3,800 troops from Afghanistan during 2013] BBC, 19 December 2012</ref> Combat operations are projected to end in 2014. Between 2001 and May 2012 a total of 414 British military personnel have died on operations in Afghanistan.<ref>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/FactSheets/OperationsFactsheets/OperationsInAfghanistanBritishFatalities.htm Operations in Afghanistan: British Fatalities] Defence factsheet</ref>

=== Iraq War ===
{{Main|Iraq War|Operation Telic}}
[[File:Land Rover Defender 110 patrol vehicles.jpg|thumb|right|British soldiers in March 2003, during the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].]]
In 2003, the United Kingdom was a major contributor to the  [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]], sending a force that would reach 46,000 military personnel.<ref>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/FactSheets/OperationsFactsheets/OperationsInIraqFactsandFigures.htm Operations in Iraq: Facts and figures] Defence factsheet</ref> The British Army controlled the southern regions of Iraq and maintained a peace-keeping presence in the city of [[Basra]] until their withdrawal on 30 April 2009. 179 British Military personnel have died on operations in Iraq.<ref>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/FactSheets/OperationsFactsheets/OperationsInIraqBritishFatalities.htm Operations in Iraq: British Fatalities] Defence factsheet</ref> All of the remaining British troops were fully withdrawn from Iraq after the Iraqi government refused to extend their mandate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/British_Troops_Leave_Iraq_As_Mandate_Ends/1789785.html |title=British Troops Leave Iraq As Mandate Ends |publisher=Rferl.org |date=31 July 2009 |accessdate=2010-10-22|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5uKgu40Rs |archivedate = 18 November 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref>

===The Troubles===
{{Main|Operation Banner}}
[[File:South Belfast 1981.jpg|thumbnail|right|British Army patrol in South Belfast during [[the Troubles]].]]
Although having permanent garrisons there, the British Army was initially deployed in a peacekeeping role – codenamed "Operation Banner" – in [[Northern Ireland]] in the wake of Unionist attacks on Nationalist communities in [[Derry]]<ref>[[Kenneth Bloomfield|Bloomfield, K]] Stormont in Crisis (Belfast 1994) p 114</ref> and [[Belfast]]<ref>[[Public Record Office of Northern Ireland|PRONI]]: Cabinet conclusions file CAB/4/1460</ref> and to prevent further Loyalist attacks on Catholic communities, under [[Operation Banner]] between 1969 and 2007 in support of the [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]] (RUC) and its successor, the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] (PSNI).<ref name="hist">{{cite book | last = McKernan | first = Michael | authorlink = | title = Northern Ireland in 1897–2004 Yearbook 2005 | publisher = Stationery Office | year = 2005 | page = 17 | doi =  | isbn = 978-0-9546284-2-0 }}</ref> There has been a steady reduction in the number of troops deployed in Northern Ireland since the [[Good Friday Agreement]] was signed in 1998.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/859388.stm Army dismantles NI post] BBC News, 31 July 2000</ref> In 2005, after the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] announced an end to its armed conflict in Northern Ireland, the British Army dismantled posts and withdrew many troops, and restored troop levels to that of a peace-time garrison.<ref>[http://www.skyscrapernews.com/news.php?ref=391 Army To Dismantle Tower Block Post] Skyscrapernews, 2 August 2005</ref>

Operation Banner ended at midnight on 31 July 2007, bringing to an end some 38 years of continuous deployment, making it the longest in the British Army's history.<ref name=analysis>{{cite web|url=http://www.patfinucanecentre.org/misc/opbanner.pdf|title=Operation Banner: An analysis of military operations in Northern Ireland|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]|year=2006|accessdate=2008-03-21|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080227094451/http://www.patfinucanecentre.org/misc/opbanner.pdf |archivedate = 27 February 2008}}</ref> An internal British Army document released in 2007 stated that the British Army had failed to defeat the IRA but had made it impossible for them to win through the use of violence. Operation Helvetic replaced Operation Banner in 2007 maintaining fewer servicemen in a much more benign environment.<ref name=analysis/><ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/6276416.stm|title=Army paper says IRA not defeated|publisher=BBC News|date=6 July 2007|accessdate=2008-03-21|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5uKgvm8RR |archivedate = 18 November 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref> From 1971 to 1997 a total of 763 British military personnel were killed during the "Troubles".<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11743727 Remembrance Day: Where they fell] BBC News, 13 November 2010</ref> Some 300 deaths during the conflict were attributed to the British Army, including paramilitary and civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/tables/index.html |title=Tabulations (Tables) of Basic Variables |publisher=Cain.ulst.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> A total of 303 RUC officers were killed in the same time period. In March 2009, two soldiers and a Police Officer were killed in separate dissident republican attacks in Northern Ireland.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7933990.stm Policeman shot dead in N Ireland] BBC News, 10 March 2009</ref>

== Current deployments ==

=== High intensity operations ===
{| class="wikitable"
|-
!Country!!Dates!!Deployment!!Details
|-
! [[Afghanistan]]
| 2001– || 6,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bfbs.com/radio/article/1000-less-soldiers-deploy-on-herrick-18-0 |title=1000 less soldiers deploy on HERRICK 18 &#124; BFBS Radio |publisher=Bfbs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> troops|| British troops have been based in Afghanistan since the [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|US-led invasion]] there in 2001. Currently, under [[Operation Herrick]], the Army maintains troops in Camp Souter, [[Kabul]] and a brigade on 6-monthly rotation in the southern province of [[Helmand Province|Helmand]], mostly based in [[Camp Bastion]] and forward operating bases. As of November 2013 the 19th Deployment (Herrick 19) is underway. In December 2012 Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] announced that 3,800 troops - almost half of the force serving in Helmand Province - would be withdrawn during 2013 with numbers to fall to approximately 5,200. Combat operations are projected to end in 2014.<ref name=ukwithdrawal/>
|}

