== Formation and structure ==
{{British Army Arms}}
{{Main|Structure of the British Army}}

The structure of the British Army is complex, due to the different origins of its various constituent parts. It is broadly split into the Regular Army (full-time Officers/soldiers and units) and the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] (Spare-time Officers/soldiers and units).

In terms of its military structure, it has two parallel organisations, one administrative and one operational.

'''Administrative'''
* Regiments and Corps. These are listed below (in the template to the right), ranging from the [[Household Cavalry]] to the [[Army Physical Training Corps]] and the [[Royal Logistic Corps]]. Uniquely and somewhat confusingly, the Infantry, which is not a corps but a collection of separate regiments, is administered by 'Divisions' of infantry – [[Guards Division]], [[Queen's Division]], [[Scottish Division]] and so on.<ref>Heyman, p.105</ref>

'''Operational'''
* The major operational command is based at [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]] and is known as "[[Army Headquarters (United Kingdom)|Army Headquarters]]".<ref name=intel>[http://www.dmilt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2506:uk-army-command-reorganization&catid=1:europe&Itemid=57 Army Command reorganization] Defence Marketing Intelligence, 10 November 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/structure/142.aspx |title=Higher Command |publisher=Army.mod.uk |date=1 November 2011 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> It is split into divisions and subordinate units ranging from regiments to squadrons.
* [[Division (military)|Divisions]] (1 Div. based in [[Herford]] in Germany and 3 Div. based in [[Bulford]])<ref>Heyman, p. 92</ref>
** [[Brigade]]s, both fighting and in a non fighting regional capacity within HQ LF (for example, 43 (Wessex) [[Brigade]] based in [[Bulford]]).

===Structure of units===

The standard operational units are structured as follows, although various units have their own structure, conventions, names and sizes:<ref name="SAS">{{cite web
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
